09948nam a22021015i 9780691228242DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222000nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759487  a97806912282427 a10.1515/97806912282422doi  a(DE-B1597)576671  a(OCoLC)1312726521  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBL65.P7 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a322/.122200aObligations of Citizenship and Demands of Faith :bReligious Accommodation in Pluralist Democracies /ced. by Nancy L. Rosenblum. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Pluralism, Integralism, and Political Theories of Religious Accommodation -- t1. Civil Religion Revisited: Quiet Faith in Middle-Class America -- t2. Public Religion: Bane or Blessing for Democracy? -- t3. Believers as Equal Citizens -- t4. Illusory Pluralism, Inexorable Establishment -- t5. Religion and State in the United States: A Defense of Two-Way Protection -- t6. Amos: Religious Autonomy and the Moral Uses of Pluralism -- t7. Five Questions about Religion Judges Are Afraid to Ask -- t8. The Fullness of Time -- t9. Let Them Eat Incidentals: RFRA, the Rehnquist Court, and Freedom of Religion -- t10. "By the Light of Reason": Corruption, Religious Speech, and Constitutional Essentials -- t11. Remember Amalek: Religious Hate Speech -- t12. Religion and Women's Equality: The Case of India -- t13. Women and International Human Rights: Some Issues under the Bridge -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOf the many challenges facing liberal democracy, none is as powerful and pervasive today as those posed by religion. These are the challenges taken up in Obligations of Citizenship and Demands of Faith, an exploration of the place of religion in contemporary public life. The essays in this volume suggest that two important shifts have altered the balance between the competing obligations of citizenship and faith: the growth of religious pluralism and the escalating calls of religious groups for some measure of autonomy or recognition from democratic majorities. The authors--political theorists, philosophers, legal scholars, and social scientists--collectively argue that more room should be made for religion in today's democratic societies. Though they advocate different ways of carving out and justifying the proper bounds of "church and state" in pluralist democracies, they all write from within democratic theory and share the aim of democratic accommodation of religion. Alert to national differences in political circumstances and the particularities of constitutional and legal systems, these contributors consider the question of religious accommodation from the standpoint of institutional practices and law as well as that of normative theory. Unique in its interdisciplinary approach and comparative focus, this volume makes a timely and much-needed intervention in current debates about religion and politics. The contributors are Nancy L. Rosenblum, Alan Wolfe, Ronald Thiemann, Michael McConnell, Graham Walker, Amy Gutmann, Kent Greenawalt, Aviam Soifer, Harry Hirsch, Gary Jacobsohn, Yael Tamir, Martha Nussbaum, and Carol Weisbrod.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCitizenshipxReligious aspects. 0aDemocracyxReligious aspects. 0aDemocracy. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aReligion and politics. 0aReligion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAlan Wolfe.  aAmendment.  aAmericans.  aAttempt.  aBaptists.  aBuddhism.  aCatholic Church.  aChristianity.  aCitizenship.  aCi